---
description: Enforce RTL-safe, bilingual-correct layout and content handling in React/TypeScript
alwaysApply: false
globs: ["**/*.tsx", "**/*.css", "!**/*.test.*", "!**/*.spec.*"]
---

## What This Rule Does

`react-i18n-rtl-gen` already generates RTL-correct code when explicitly
invoked for a component or feature, but nothing previously stopped
*ordinary* component generation (`react-component-gen`, hand-written code, or
ports from non-RTL examples) from introducing physical-direction CSS or
LTR-only assumptions that silently break once `dir="rtl"` is applied. Given
this workspace's GCC fintech context, Arabic-locale support isn't an edge
case — it's a primary, professional-requirement use case, and a layout bug
that only manifests in RTL mode is exactly the kind of thing that's easy to
miss in development (where most engineers default to viewing the LTR
locale) and embarrassing to ship.

Note the naming disambiguation: elsewhere in this workspace, "RTL" inside
`03-react-architecture-guard.mdc`'s testing table refers to React Testing
Library. In this rule, "RTL" always means right-to-left layout direction.

**Memory references:** `memory-bank/frontendConventions.md`,
`memory-bank/glossary.md` (bilingual terminology consistency).

---

## What Gets Refused

- Physical CSS direction properties on any new or modified component:
  `margin-left`/`margin-right`, `padding-left`/`padding-right`,
  `text-align: left`/`text-align: right`, `left`/`right` positioning,
  `border-left`/`border-right` — the logical equivalents
  (`margin-inline-start/end`, `padding-inline-start/end`, `text-align: start`,
  `inset-inline-start/end`, `border-inline-start/end`) are required instead,
  since these flip automatically with `dir`.
- Hardcoded directional icons (a "next" chevron pointing right) with no
  `dir`-aware mirroring — either use an icon component that respects
  `dir` via CSS `transform: scaleX(-1)` under `[dir="rtl"]`, or a
  direction-neutral icon.
- String concatenation that assumes word order (`firstName + " " + lastName`,
  or building a sentence from interpolated fragments) — Arabic sentence
  structure doesn't always match English word order; use a single
  translation key with placeholders (`t('greeting', { name })`) instead of
  assembling translated fragments at the call site.
- Number/currency/date formatting via manual string building instead of
  `Intl.NumberFormat`/`Intl.DateTimeFormat` with the active locale — SAR
  amounts and Hijri/Gregorian date display both depend on this being
  locale-aware, not hardcoded to one format.

## What's Warned, Not Blocked

- A component with no RTL-specific styling at all because it has no
  direction-sensitive layout (e.g. a perfectly square icon button) — flagged
  only as a reminder to verify, not refused, since not every component
  needs RTL handling.
- Mixed-direction content (an English error code embedded in an Arabic
  sentence) without explicit `dir="ltr"` wrapping on the embedded fragment —
  common and often unavoidable (gateway error codes, reference numbers), but
  worth a visual check since unwrapped mixed content can render with
  unexpected character ordering.

## Required for Any New Bilingual-Facing Component

- Verify both locales render correctly, not just that the translation key
  exists — a missing translation falling back to the key string itself
  (`payment.refund.confirm`) instead of English text is a worse failure than
  falling back to English, since it's both broken and harder to notice in a
  quick visual check.
- If the component includes user-generated or external content (gateway
  response messages, broker-submitted text), don't assume it's pre-translated
  — confirm whether it needs `dir="auto"` so the browser detects direction
  per-paragraph based on content, since externally-sourced text may not
  match the active UI locale's direction.

---

## Example Violation

**Trigger:** Generated `TransactionSummaryCard` component uses
`padding-left: 16px` and `text-align: right` for a price column, with a
hardcoded `→` character for a "view details" affordance.

**What gets flagged:**
> This component uses physical CSS properties (`padding-left`,
> `text-align: right`) that won't flip when `dir="rtl"` is applied — under
> Arabic locale, the price column will stay left-padded and right-aligned
> in the wrong direction relative to the rest of the RTL layout. Replace
> with `padding-inline-start: 16px` and `text-align: end`. The `→`
> character should be replaced with a `ChevronRight` icon component that
> mirrors via `[dir="rtl"] & { transform: scaleX(-1) }`, or swapped for a
> direction-neutral indicator.
